# Code Comments: Explain Why, Not What

Add a short one-line comment above any block of code whose purpose isn't immediately obvious. The comment should explain **why** the code exists or **what constraint** it encodes — not narrate what the code does.

```python
# ✅ GOOD — explains the reason or constraint

# Deduplicate the list if utens
my_items = list(set(my_items))

# The first two dimensions are height then width
h, w = image.shape[0], image.shape[1]

# Bradley-Terry requires at least two items to compare
if len(items) < 2:
    return


# ❌ BAD — narrates what the code does (obvious from reading it)

# Convert list to set then back to list
my_items = list(set(my_items))

# Get height and width
h, w = image.shape[0], image.shape[1]

# Check length
if len(items) < 2:
    return
```

## Rules

- One line only — if you need more, the code itself needs simplifying
- Place the comment on the line directly above the code it describes
- Skip comments for code that is self-evident from good naming alone
- Never use comments to narrate the code (e.g. `# Import the module`, `# Return the result`)
